Certainly! Here's an example of how a table of contents can be generated automatically in a LaTeX document:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tocloft}

\makeatletter
\newtoks\tableofcontents
\newtoks\@currentheading

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%% Function to count sections and subsections %%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\def\countsections#1#2{\addtocounter{section}{#1}
  \addtocounter{subsection}{#2} }

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%% Function to add special numbers to first sections and subsections %%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\def\addchapternumber#1{\refstepcounter{chapter} %
  \addcontentsline{toc}{chapter}{\protect\numberline{\thechapter}#1} }

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%% Function to add special numbers to first sections and subsections %%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\def\addsectionnumber#1{\refstepcounter{section} %
  \addcontentsline{toc}{section}{\protect\numberline{\thechapter.\theintsectnumber}{section}~~~~~#1}}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%% Function to add special numbers to first sections and subsections %%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\def\addsubsectionnum#1{\refstepcounter{subsection} %
  \addcontentsline{toc}{section}{\protect\numberline{\thechapter.\theintsectnumber.}{\theintensenum}.\theintsubensens}{#1}}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%% Function to add chapters, sections, and subsections %%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\def\addChapter#1#2{#1\addchapternumber{~} #2\addsectionnumber{} #3\addsubsectionnum{}}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%% Function to define macros %%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\makeatother

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\addChapter{Introduction}{1>Introduction}{}
\addsection{Background}{2>Background}
\addsubsection{History}{2.1}
\addsubsection{Overview}{2.2}
\addsection{Literature Review}{3>Literature Review}
\addsubsection{Backgrounds}{3.1}
\addsubsection{Conclusions}{3.2}
\addsection{Methodology}{4>Methodology}
\addsubsection{Sampling}{4.1}
\addsubsection{Data Collection and Analysis}{4.2}
\addsection{Results and Discussion}{5>Results and Discussion}
\addsubsection{Data Analysis}{5.1}
\addsubsection{Results}{5.2}
\addsection{Conclusion}{6>Conclusion}

\end{document}
```
This example uses the `tocloft` package to format the table of contents automatically. Here's how it works:

1. Adjust your needed TOC levels: The tocloft package provides many customisation options, included are levels of Chapter, Section, and Subsection. In this example, 3 levels are used: chapter, section, and subsection.
2. Define the chapters, sections, and subsections: The language in the `\addChapter` command defines the chapter headings. Each section or subsection is defined with its level, chapter name, title, and content. In this example, three chapter headings are created.
3. Call the `tocloft` package: The `tocloft` package is used to format the table of contents using the commands defined in step 2. 

I hope this example helps you generate a table of contents in your LaTeX document. If you have any more questions, let me know!

To create a chessboard diagram in LaTeX with FEN notation, you can use the `chessboard` package developed by Jesse Johnson. This package provides `\newchessboard` command to create a standard chessboard, with optional FEN notation. Below is an example of how to use the `chessboard` package to draw a chessboard with FEN notation in your LaTeX document:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}
\newchessboard[setfen=(3,3,3)r,hspace=1,mathcode=\^(+2100),startpos=(A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2)]
\end{center}

\end{document}
```
In this example, we've used the following FEN notation to represent the position:
```diff
3k4/3Pp/3p1p1/3P1P1/8/8/8 w - - 0 1
```
Here, the FEN notation `(3,3,3)` represents a standard chess board (with 8x8 cells). The `r` sign at the end specifies that the position needs to be reflected horizontally to display correctly on your chess board image. The `chessboard` package also offers several options to customize the board, such as `hspace`, `mathrule`, and `startpos`.

Additionally, you can customize the appearance of the chessboard and its pieces using various options provided by the `chessboard` package. Here's an updated example with some customizations:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}
\newchessboard[setfen=(3,3,3)r,hspace=1,mathcode=\^(+2100),startpos=(A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2,A2),symbolsize=2cm,figsize=3cm,figure=false,dotsize=4,dotspecs=(3,3)]
\end{center}

\end{document}
```
In this example, we've added options such as `symbolsize`, `figsize`, `figure`, `dotsize`, and `dotspecs`, to adjust the board's appearance, ranging from the size of the pieces to the spacing of dots (highlighting game progress).

