import java.math.BigInteger;

public class PowerOfThree {

    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // Check for small values first
        if (n <= -231 || n >= 231 - 1) {
            return false;
        }

        // Convert n to a BigInteger for easier bit manipulation
        BigInteger bi = BigInteger.valueOf(n);

        // Shift the most significant bit until the leftmost 1 is in the least significant bit
        BigInteger shifted = bi.shiftLeft(1);

        // Bitwise AND with the original BigInteger. This will give us the most significant bit
        BigInteger mask = shifted.and(bi);

        // Check if the most significant bit is non-zero
        return mask.intValue() != 0;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int n = 27;
        if (isPowerOfThree(n)) {
            System.out.println(n + " is a power of three");
        } else {
            System.out.println(n + " is not a power of three");
        }
    }
}
```
In this solution, we first check for small values which are easy to handle with a simple check. Then we convert the integer n to a BigInteger and use bit manipulation to check if it's a power of three or not. Finally, we print the result based on the comparison.

